       Aminet(18) - util/arc/DaUUDirector111.lha
       Aminet(19) - util/wb/shitstrip12b.lha
     @{b}triton.library @{ub}           by Stefan Zeiger                             @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check Libs:triton.library 6.115"}
       You will most probably need at least Version 6.115 of this
       library, since the RecoverDelDir prefs program failed to
       open under V5.5 when I tried it on my test partition.
       AminetSet1A:aminet/dev/gui/
       Aminet( 9) - util/rexx/TritonRexx376.lha
       Aminet(10) - util/rexx/TRX_Tools.lha
       Aminet(11) - misc/amag/AMS96011b.lha
       Aminet(12) - util/cdity/MoronCX10.lha
       Aminet(19) - dev/gui/tri20b2usr.lha
       Aminet(22) - util/time/EngClock86.lha
       Aminet(23) - gfx/misc/PicSort2.lha
     @{b}png.datatype@{ub} (akPNG.dataype, for example)
       to view the pics contained in this guide.                            @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Lister Sys:Classes/Datatypes"}
     @{b}rexxsupport.library@{ub}                                                    @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check Libs:rexxsupport.library"}
     @{b}locale.library@{ub} for non-english languages                               @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check Libs:locale.library"}

     L:@{b}HarddiskAFS@{ub}         V 16.16  @{fg shine}@{b}Ami File Safe@{ub}@{fg text} Professional   (PFS1)     @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check L:HardDiskAFS"}
     or
     L:@{b}pfs2@{ub}                V 17.8   @{fg shine}@{b}Professional File System II@{ub}@{fg text}  (PFS2)     @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check L:pfs2"}
     or
     L:@{b}SmartFileSystem@{ub}     V  1.13  @{fg shine}@{b}SmartFileSystem@{ub}@{fg text} (beta)       (SFS0)     @{" Check " rx "/ARexx/Check L:SmartFileSystem"}

     and a device formatted using any of this file systems.


     _______________________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

     This program has been extensively @{b}tested@{ub} on my own machine,
     which has the following specs:

     A 2000, WB3.1, Blizzard 2060/50, 64MB, Picasso_II 800x600x256 CybergraphX 2.x
     Directory Opus 5.661 Magellan running as WB replacemnt,
     Screenmode setting: Use WB.
     RexxMast              V  36.5
     tritonrexx.library    V  37.7
     triton.library        V   6.115
     rexxtricks.library    V  38.6
     akPNG.datatype        V 181

     L:HarddiskAFS         V 16.16  Ami File Safe Professional   (PFS1)
     L:pfs2                V 17.8   Professional File System II  (PFS2)
     L:SmartFileSystem     V  1.13  SmartFileSystem (beta)       (SFS0)

     _______________________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

     @{b}Known Incompatibilites@{ub}

     devices using FFS (FFSx)
     disks using AFS   (PFS0)

     Neither of these have the .deldir directory which is required for
     this program to work.

     devices using SFS
     on which the .deldir directory has been deleted or moved.

     If you don't have at least Version5.5 of DOpus Magellan (I),
     you won't be able to start RecoverDelDir by doubleclicking its
     icon.


     _______________________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

     If you should encounter an error requester
     with the gadget @{"Save report as RAM:RDD.Error" link "ram:RDD.Error/main"},
     please send me the resulting file (ram:RDD.Error)

     _______________________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

     If something doesn't work like it should     Also reread the chapters about
     (eg. certain windows do not open), please    installation and preferences.
     doublecheck if your system suits all
     requirements.


@endnode
@NODE "INSTALL" "Installing RecoverDelDir"
@PREV "Require"
@TOC "MAIN"


         @{b}Important note!@{ub}

         If not yet done, please @{b}unpack@{ub} the file 'RecoverDelDir.lha' somewhere.

         Please keep @{" all files " link "/recoverdeldir.contents/Main"} in their place and
         do not change the directory structure, because this guide contains links to
         some of them and therefore won't function correctly if you rename, move or delete
         any of these files.

         Please do not change the directory structure. This document must not be
         copied somewhere else, either, or it will not work correctly.
      
         You'd best simply leave the whole package in place after unpacking it
         and start this guide from within the resulting directory.
         This ensures that the guide will find everything it needs.


         ____________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         ------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

         @{u}@{b}To install RecoverDelDir on your system, follow these steps:@{uu}@{ub}


         If you have DOpus running, all Hyperlinks on this page
         ending on "/" will open a new DOpus-lister displaying the
         appropiate path.

         These listers will help you in following the installation
         procedure @{b}step by step@{ub}.

         You'd best reduce the window height of this guide, so that
         the listers are not hidden by the guide window.

         Off we go:


         Take a look into the directory @{" DOpus5:Tools/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister DOpus5:Tools RecoverDelDir DESTLOCK"}.
         If there already is a directory named @{b}RecoverDelDir@{ub}, please
         @{u}rename@{uu} it.

         Now copy the entire @{" RecoverDelDir/ " rx "/ARexx/lister // RecoverDelDir SOURCELOCK"} directory
         to @{" DOpus5:Tools/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister DOpus5:Tools REQ Please copy the directory `RecoverDelDir` into this directory DESTLOCK"}.

         Copy the file @{b}ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5@{ub} and the directory
         @{b}Defaultstrings@{ub} (including its contents) from the @{" ARexx/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister /ARexx Defaultstrings RecoverDelDir.dopus5 SOURCELOCK"}@{"?" rx "/ARexx/SystemReq Please copy these:*n*nRecoverDelDir/ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5*nRecoverDelDir/ARexx/Defaultstrings (Dir)*nRecoverDelDir/ARexx/Defaultstrings/RecoverDelDir.strings"}
         directory into the directory @{" DOpus5:ARexx/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister DOpus5:ARexx REQ Please copy the directory `Defaultstrings` and the file `RecoverDelDir.dopus5` into this directory  DESTLOCK"}@{"?" rx "/ARexx/SystemReq -> DOpus5:ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5*n-> DOpus5:ARexx/Defaultstrings (Dir)*n-> DOpus5:ARexx/Defaultstrings/RecoverDelDir.strings"}.

         Copy @{b}all files@{ub} from within the directory @{" Prefs/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister /Prefs RecoverDelDirPrefs RecoverDelDirPrefs.info RecoverDelDir.prefs SOURCELOCK"}@{"?" rx "/ARexx/SystemReq Files to be copied:*n*nRecoverDelDir/Prefs/RecoverDelDir.prefs*nRecoverDelDir/Prefs/RecoverDelDirPrefs*nRecoverDelDir/Prefs/RecoverDelDirPrefs.info"}
         to the destination @{" SYS:Prefs/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister SYS:Prefs REQ Please copy the files 'RecoverDelDirPrefs' 'RecoverDelDirPrefs.info' and 'RecoverDelDir.prefs' into this directory DESTLOCK"}@{"?" rx "/ARexx/SystemReq -> SYS:Prefs/RecoverDelDir.prefs*n-> SYS:Prefs/RecoverDelDirPrefs*n-> SYS:Prefs/RecoverDelDirPrefs.info"}
         

         The next step is to setup DirectoryOpus to use the script, e.g. via
         the listers' @{b}popup menu@{ub}.

         @{fg shine}@{b}-------------------------------------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}
         @{b}ARexx@{ub}   @{fg shine}@{b}DOpus5:ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}{Qp} {Ql}@{ub}
         Options: "Run asynchronously"
         @{fg shine}@{b}-------------------------------------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

         You'd best place this new entry somewhere near the "Delete" entry.


         _________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -----------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

         You can also start RecoverDelDir directly
         @{b}without@{ub} configuring DOpus:

         Copy the file @{FG shine}@{b}RecoverDelDir@{ub}@{FG text} from the main RDD directory
         and its icon to one of your AFS/PFS or SFS-partitions.

         This file is a @{b}DOpus command@{ub}.
         All settings which are described above are already
         contained in this file.
         It will run the ARexx script @{b}@{FG shine}DOpus5:ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5@{FG text}@{ub}

         I recommend you to install this file into a newly created
         directory called "saved Files" or "Salvation", because the
         directory you run it from will also be the directory where
         deleted files will be restored to.


         _________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -----------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

         @{b}Some notes about the configurung options:@{ub}

         Generally, setting up RecoverDelDir to be run from a
         listers popup menu is the more flexible method, because
         the restored files will always be restored to the directory
         which is displayed in the currently active source lister.

         When starting RDD via the popups, this can be any directory
         you like, but if you directly start RDD via a doubleclick like
         described above, the destination directory will in every case
         be the directory you doubleclick-started RDD from.

         _________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -----------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

         @{b}Note about the placement of the program parts:@{ub}

         Theoretically, you could start RecoverDelDir directly from
         the directory you unpacked it to, given the condition that
         the path name leading to this directory is not that lang:
         It must not consist of more than 43 characters incl.the last '/'.
         "Shortcuts" like Assigns or device names won't help to
         bypass this limitation, since ARexx doesn't seem to care
         about these.
         Additionally, you would also have to change the path name
         in the icon of the RecoverDelDir command (which defaults
         to DOpus5:ARexx/RecoverDelDir.dopus5)

         If you don't want to keep the commands 'DeviceInfo' and
         'SFSDelDirName' in the default directory, which is
         DOpus5:Tools/RecoverDelDir/C/, you will have to set their
         path in the RecoverDelDir Prefs program accordingly.

         _________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -----------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

         @{b}Installing foreing language files@{ub}

         If you'd prefer a different language
         than the built-in English to be used for
         RecoverDelDir, you'll have to do the following:

         Copy the file
         @{" Catalogs/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister /Catalogs REQ Please open the preferred language-directory and select the RecoverDelDir.catalog SOURCELOCK"} @{fg shine}@{b}<language>/@{ub}@{fg text}@{b}RecoverDelDir.Catalog@{ub}
         to
         @{" SYS:Locale/Catalogs/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister SYS:Locale/Catalogs REQ Please open the preferred language-directory and copy the RecoverDelDir.catalog into that directory DESTLOCK"} @{fg shine}@{b}<language>/@{ub}@{fg text}

         @{"Here" LINK "LOCALE" } you will find information about which
         languages RecoverDelDir has been translated to and about how
         to create a translation into your preferred language.

















@endnode
@NODE "USAGE" "RecoverDelDir Usage"
@PREV "Install"
@TOC "MAIN"


        Open a @{b}DOpus lister@{ub} (text or icon plus mode) or
        simply use the one you currently have open, regardless of
        the mode it uses (source, destination, deactivated).

        Now use the menu entry which you just created (see @{" Installation " link install}) and
        the @{" main window " LINK "/Illustration/RecoverDelDir.png/main"} of RecoverDelDir should appear.

        Alternatively, you can simply doubleclick the @{b}program@{ub} @{FG shine}@{b}RecoverDelDir@{ub}@{FG text}
        (which is a DOpus command) within a DOpus lister.
        The DelDir of this DOpus lister will be read.

        If you have just installed or updated RecoverDelDir
        the preferencesprogram will appear
        and write prefs-files to ENV: and ENVARC:
        Simply quit it using 'Cancel'.


        _________________________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}

        @{" RecoverDelDir GUI " LINK "/Illustration/RecoverDelDir.png/main"} RecoverDelDir.png

        The active @{b}Device@{ub} is displayed in the title bar, just below that you
        can see the directory which is displayed in the lister RecoverDelDir
        has been started from.
        This directory will also be the @{b}@{fg shine}destination directory@{fg text}@{ub} into which the
        undeleted file(s) will be put after undeleting.

        The gadget just to the right of this allows you to change
        the @{b}@{fg shine}destination directory@{fg text}@{ub}. After changing it, a new @{b}text lister@{ub}
        will be opened displaying the new destination directory.

        Below you see a @{b}list@{ub} displaying all @{b}files@{ub} which were
        found in the directory :@{b}@{fg shine}.recycled@{fg text}@{ub} on the chosen device.
        On the right of this list, the DOpus filetype for each single file can be seen.
        Here you can simply click the file you want to be restored.

        If you click on a filename, the following information about
        the file will be displayed in the text boxes on the bottom:

        @{fg shine}@{b}PFS@{ub}@{fg text}

          @{b}On the left@{ub} you can see the @{b}filename@{ub} as it appears
          in @{FG shine}@{b}device:.deldir@{ub}@{FG text} (e.g. with suffix)

          @{b}On the right@{ub}, you can see the @{b}filename@{ub} under which the file
          will be restored.
          It has a maximum lenght of 17 characters, exceeding characters
          are truncated by AFS/PFS2.

        @{FG shine}@{b}SFS@{ub}@{FG text}

          @{b}On the left@{ub}, you will see the @{b}filename@{ub} as it appears in
          @{b}@{FG shine}device:.deldirname@{FG text}@{ub}

          @{b}On the right@{ub}, you will see the @{b}suffix@{ub} (without $) which will be
          added to the filename if two or more files with the same filename
          are found in device:.recycled.

        If you click the @{" Restore file " rx "/ARexx/SystemReq RecoverDelDir-Button:*n*n[ Restore file ]"} gadget, a filerequester pointing to the
        current path and the filename of the currently selected file will be opened.
        Here you have the last chance to change the filename and/or the path.
        In the latter case, a new destination lister will be opened.
        Then, after final confirmation the selected file will be restored.

        If you click the @{" Doubleclick " rx "/ARexx/SystemReq RecoverDelDir-Button:*n*n[ Doubleclick ]"} gadget, the action which you defined
        as "doubleclick left" for the filetype of this particular file within
        the DOpus Filetype settings will be performed.
        So, depending on your DOpus setup, this button should be handled with care. ;-)

        @{"[]" rx "/ARexx/SystemReq RecoverDelDir-Button:*n*nThe savesymbol*non the left bottom"} Finally, on the left of the window you will see a "Save" button.
        If you click on this one, the currently displayed filelist will be saved as
        RAM:<device>_.<deldirname>.<number>

        PS:
        number = Right(CALL Pragma(ID),8"."Time('S')

        @{" Finished ! " rx "/ARexx/SystemReq RecoverDelDir-Button:*n*nWill quit*nthe program"} quits RecoverDelDir.



        @{FG shine}---------------------------@{FG text} @{b}Menu functions@{ub} @{FG shine}-----------------------------@{FG text}

        @{b}GUIDE@{ub}

          shows the guide you are currently reading

        @{b}Prefs@{ub}

          Starts RecoverDelDirs prefs program.
          While the prefs program is running, the
          RDD-window will be hidden.
          After quitting the prefs program the
          RDD main window will reappear already
          using the newly set or changed
          preferences.

@endnode

